VALUES ('e7b93ce4-61bb-441b-bdac-f3d1fe2dd98f', 'Which choice completes the text with the most logical transition?', 'Researchers revisiting a long-debated question in the field recently reported findings that have renewed scholarly discussion of the issue. The apprenticeship program paired newcomers with veteran machinists who modeled careful, deliberate technique on every shop-floor task. ______ it reimbursed tuition for evening coursework, allowing participants to deepen the theory underlying the skills they practiced daily.', 'passage', '[{"id":"A","text":"Blurring the sharp contrast the passage has drawn between the two claims,","is_correct":false,"explanation":"[Synonym Trap] Blurring the sharp contrast the passage has drawn between the two claims, This phrase suggests a different rhetorical relationship than the one required between the two clauses."},{"id":"B","text":"Qualifying the sweeping claim made in the prior sentence with added nuance,","is_correct":false,"explanation":"[Category Shift] Qualifying the sweeping claim made in the prior sentence with added nuance, This phrase suggests a different rhetorical relationship than the one required between the two clauses."},{"id":"C","text":"Extending the author''s line of reasoning further into the policy implications,","is_correct":true,"explanation":"Correct (C). Extending the author''s line of reasoning further into the policy implications, This participial phrase signals addition while preserving sentence grammar, matching Digital SAT hard transition expectations."},{"id":"D","text":"Adding a parallel example that deepens the same point about methodological limits,","is_correct":false,"explanation":"[Register Clash] Adding a parallel example that deepens the same point about methodological limits, This phrase suggests a different rhetorical relationship than the one required between the two clauses."}]'::jsonb, 'C', 'Step 1 — Identify the relationship
Focus on {{yellow:discussion}} in the passage. The transition item asks you to identify the relationship before comparing choices.

Step 2 — Test transition logic
Compare each option against explicit textual evidence. On hard items, correct answers usually restate the passage faithfully without absolute words the text does not support.

Step 3 — Complete the sentence
